members.description: The direct consumer and beneficiary of a health service (for example, a patient).

members.description: A family member or friend (not trained or certified) who provides unpaid, non-clinical care for a client who requires their assistance.

members.name: Facility-based health worker
members.description: A formally recognized member of the health system responsible for directly or indirectly providing health services, including: physicians, nurses, midwives and other clinical staff; pharmacists and laboratory technicians; environmental and public health workers

members.name: Community-based health worker
members.description: Formally recognized care provider, based in the community, providing preventive and curative services. Activity is not limited to a fixed site. Also sometimes referred to as “Frontline” or “Community” Health Workers.

members.name: Manager
members.description: One who is responsible for planning, organizing, staffing, leading or directing, and controlling human, financial and material resources, for the purposes of delivering health services. This would also include supervisors.

members.name: Health system constraint
members.description: Barriers and challenges that impede optimal health service delivery.

members.name: Availability
members.description: Physical availability and supply of health services.

members.name: Quality
members.description: Relevance and effectiveness of health services.

members.name: Acceptability
members.description: Alignment of health services with individual, social and cultural beliefs, interests, needs and practices.

members.description: Barriers at the societal level

members.name: Addressing individual beliefs and practices
members.description: Barriers at the individual level

members.name: Efficiency
members.description: Time or effort required to implement health services.

members.name: Cost
members.description: Monetary expense related to the delivery or use of health services.

members.description: Does it function as intended?

members.description: How well does it work? What effects does it have?

members.description: Can it work as well in a larger population?

members.name: Scaled program
members.description: How well can it be sustained and optimized for additional populations?

members.name: Feasibility
members.description: Determining appropriate solution to problem

members.name: Functionality
members.description: Does it work as intended?

members.name: Usability
members.description: Is it able to be used effectively?

members.name: Effectiveness

members.name: Optimization

STIs, excluding HIV
members.description: Sexually transmitted infections (STIs) are infections that are spread primarily through person-to-person sexual contact. There are more than 30 different sexually transmissible bacteria, viruses and parasites. The most common conditions they cause are gonorrhoea, chlamydial infection, syphilis, trichomoniasis, chancroid, genital herpes, genital warts. http://www.who.int/topics/sexually_transmitted_infections/en/

members.name: Respiratory tract infections (URI, LRI, OM)
members.description: Respiratory tract diseases are diseases that affect the air passages, including the nasal passages, the bronchi and the lungs. They include acute infections, such as pneumonia and bronchitis. http://www.who.int/topics/respiratory_tract_diseases/en/

members.name: Cancer
members.description: Cancer is the uncontrolled growth and spread of cells. http://www.who.int/topics/cancer/en/

members.name: Diabetes
members.description: Diabetes is a chronic disease, which occurs when the pancreas does not produce enough insulin, or when the body cannot effectively use the insulin it produces. This leads to an increased concentration of glucose in the blood (hyperglycaemia). http://www.who.int/topics/diabetes_mellitus/en/

members.name: Cardiovascular disease
members.description: Cardiovascular disease is caused by disorders of the heart and blood vessels, and includes coronary heart disease (heart attacks), cerebrovascular disease (stroke), raised blood pressure (hypertension), peripheral artery disease, rheumatic heart disease, congenital heart disease and heart failure. http://www.who.int/topics/cardiovascular_diseases/en/

members.name: Asthma
members.description: Asthma is a chronic disease characterized by recurrent attacks of breathlessness and wheezing, which vary in severity and frequency from person to person. During an asthma attack, the lining of the bronchial tubes swells, causing the airways to narrow and reducing the flow of air into and out of the lungs. http://www.who.int/topics/asthma/en/

members.name: Nutrition
members.description: Nutrition disorders can be caused by an insufficient intake of food or of certain nutrients, by an inability of the body to absorb and use nutrients, or by overconsumption of certain foods. Examples include obesity caused by excess energy intake, anaemia caused by insufficient intake of iron, and impaired sight because of inadequate intake of vitamin A. http://www.who.int/topics/nutrition_disorders/en/

members.description: Treatment of an accident or illness that will require less time to recover and is not life threatening

members.name: Acute or emergency
members.description: The care for an acute care patient is normally brief but classified as severe illness, accidents or trauma

members.name: Chronic care
members.description: Previously existing conditions or conditions that will require a long period of time to care for it, that may not require institutionalization.

members.name: Long term institutionalized care
members.description: With long term institutionalized care the person involved whether by accident, illness, injury or disease cannot perform normal daily functions without assistance from another person or object.

members.name: Health education or promotion
members.description: “Health education is any combination of learning experiences designed to help individuals and communities improve their health, by increasing their knowledge or influencing their attitudes.” (http://www.who.int/topics/health_education/en/). This includes intervention tasks such as counseling on or promoting healthy behaviors. E.g.: Information and counseling on birth planning, advice on labor, danger signs and emergency preparedness.

members.name: Disease prevention
members.description: “Prevention refers to interventions that occur before the initial onset of disorder or disease.“ Includes intervention tasks such as support of healthy behaviors or distribution of preventive commodities and supplies. (http://healthvermont.gov/adap/prevention/prevention_fact.aspx) E.g., Malaria prevention through the use of bednet; Prevention of anemia through iron-folate supplementation; Distribution of contraceptives

members.name: Disease diagnosis / Point-of-care diagnostics
members.description: Diagnosis refers to the “ techniques and procedures” that “encompass all investigations and tests intended to identify the cause of an illness or disorder. They include, for example, laboratory tests for infectious agents, and imaging techniques, such as radiology and ultrasound examination. “ (http://www.who.int/topics/diagnostic_techniques_procedures/en/) This includes intervention tasks such as screening, detection, identification, recognition, and monitoring. e.g., HIV testing

members.name: Disease management
members.description: Disease management is defined as "a system of coordinated health care interventions and communications for populations with conditions in which patient self-care efforts are significant. (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disease_management_%28health%29) Includes intervention tasks relating to support, maintenance, and follow up of care e.g: Support for women living with HIV/AIDS

members.name: Referrals
members.description: gm- “Referral systems ensure that patients with health conditions that cannot be adequately addressed by their current location in the health system, are directed in a manner that reflects the client needs, to the specific provider or appropriate level and type of health system facility where the client can gain the services that are needed without requiring additional referral or undue costs to the client or health system.” e.g.: Referral of children with severe illness.

members.name: Data collection and reporting
members.description:
Defined as recording information on patient health and service provision using paper-based or electronic systems, and any standards that are used to provide an periodic account of events at the individual, case or aggregate level. e.g., Service updates to patient health record; district-level vaccination coverage data; compatibility and consistency of health information and data as per International Organization for Standardization guidelines.
